undamental barrier between human beings and animals and the limits of the state in the face of the natural lives of its subjects, as well as territorial frontiers. Drawing on a wide range of authors, Brett reveals how early modern political space was constructed from a complex dynamic of inclusion and exclusion. Throughout, she shows that early modern debates about political boundaries displayed unheralded creativity and virtuosity but were nevertheless vulnerable to innumerable paradoxes, contradictions, and loose ends. Changes of State is a major work of intellectual history that resonates with modern debates about globalization and the transformation of the nation-state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBoundaries (Philosophy). 0aBoundariesxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 0aNatural law. 0aState, ThexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aState, ThexOrigin. 0aState, ThexPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh  aAristotelian thinking.  aCatholic scholastic tradition.  aDomingo de Soto.  aEuropean states.  aFrancisco de Vitoria.  aLeviathan.  aPeace of Westphalia.  aProtestant jurists.  aProtestant natural law.  aSpanish School of Salamanca.  aThomas Aquinas.  aThomas Hobbes.  aalterity.  aanimal behavior.  aanti-Aristotelian.  abody politic.  acity.  acivil law.  acivil liberty.  acivil war.  acommonwealth.  adominium.  aearly modern politics.  aexternal movement.  afree agency.  afreedom.  aglobalization.  ahuman agency.  ahuman beings.  ahuman will.  aindividual agency.  ajuridical entity.  alaw of humanity.  alaw.  alegal humanist thinking.  alocal motion.  alocomotion.  amoral philosophy.  anation-state.  anatural body.  anatural faculty.  anatural law discourse.  anatural law.  anatural liberty.  anatural mastery.  